The leaf blades are wide spreading and opposite- and are leaves not leaflets (poison sumac has compound leaves, sumac-y but shiny and no teeth). The habitat is upland looking, poison sumac usually (of course not always) in wetlands, often peaty (or not quite peaty) areas. Poison sumac is woody with thick branches, alternate compound leaves, that do have red rachises.. There are 2 dogbane species in New England. I think this is spreading dogbane, the other has more upright, narrower leaves.	47359								Apocynum androsaemifolium L.
